Video Title: Tarsier Monkeys are the smallest in the World Bohol, Philippines
Video Description:
We were so excited to see these amazing little Tarsier Monkeys that we could have screamed, but if we screamed these little nocturnal creatures would get stressed.  When they get stressed they have been known to commit suicide, so we had to be very quiet.  Their brains are smaller than their eyes and they have the largest eyes (compared to the body size) of all mammals. Tarsiers are carnivorous animals and catch their prey by leaping from one branch to another.  As we walked through the park they were very hard to spot, the only way you really knew where one was was by looking for the crowds of people checking them out and snapping photos.  They are the cutest little creatures I have ever seen (besides kittens) they are nestled up and hugging the branches it was absolutley adorable.  They even look like they are smiling at you- gaaahhhhhhhhh let my heart be still!
We had a BLAST visiting these small wonders and it remains one of our highlights in the Philippines.

Video Title: Taxi Scam is Real in the Philippines - Reacting To Hayley Dasovich Taxi Scam Vlog
Video Description:
Click here to SUBSCRIBE to my channel: bit.ly/2JmVUgq
To see the whole taxi scam incident check the out the videos below:

Haley's Vlog on Taxi Scam
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=84rn8P53uJY

Haley's reaction video on the taxi scam
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wg4NNW--yxg&t=154s


Taxi scams in the Philippines is nothing new. It has been around for numerous years, kinda likes how corruption is ever present there. This video is about me watching the news regarding the taxi scam incident in Manila that occurred last week as well as watching Haley's reaction video of the incident - putting my personal opinion and also sharing my experience as I traveled to the Philippines a couple of months ago.

Quick tip if you are travelling to the Philippines, research the destination of where you are going and make sure you equip yourself with a lot of information. Also use Uber or Grab (I mainly use Uber when I'm in the Philippines).

For example, I did a google search on Manila International Airport, I look at the website and click transportation taxi and this came up:

Scams

Manila Airport is wide famous for its scams regarding taxi services. It is wisely to take only the official, metered or pre-booked taxis. Given this fact, do not accept rides from people that approach you in the terminal â€“ You may possibly be a victim of a scam.

In order to avoid scams, it is advisable to carry small bills, having your destination written down in a piece of paper and knowing the approximate fare of your trip to avoid being ripped off.

It is advisable to be special careful with the so-called Manila Concierges, which will ask you a tip for supposedly helping you hailing a taxi.


As you plan your trip, take the time to plan your public transport trips as well as your hotel stays. Find out about typical fares from the airport to your hotel, or from your hotel to the attractions you wish to visit. 

Check the web page here:
https://www.manila-airport.net/taxi.php

Stay safe and happy travels!

Thank you for watching!

Video Title: Crazy Toy Shopping in Greenhills Philippines Travel Vlog
Video Description:
Click here to SUBSCRIBE to my channel: bit.ly/2JmVUgq

Toy shopping here is crazy! There are so many toys to choose from!

So my family and I went to Greenhills Shopping Center in the Philippines. You can probably spend  4 hours there. There are plenty of things to buy there ranging from toys, second hand goods, pearls, Jewellery, fake shoes, fake watches, cheap electronics, souvenirs, sea shells, t-shirts, shorts, bags, even collectibles. 

The whole Greenhills shopping center is like a combination of a multiple shopping malls (Virra Mall, Shoppesville, Theatre Mall) , Unimart (you can buy groceries here), food court and indoor/outdoor flea market or night market or bazaar. 
Be very careful as it can be quite crowded especially during the holidays where pretty all tourists goes there to buy stuff.

Generally what you can find is that the second floor has all electronics, phones, tablets, power banks, etc. and and they also do repairs if you bust your phone or tablet and need repairs.
 
Parking here is insane, even picking up people is insane. Best bet - Uber or Grab, very cheap, just get picked up a block away.

Remember to bring cash as you can haggle. You can find ATM machines though

You can use credit card on some shops although I will only use it on legit shops such as Toy Kingdom, Converse Store, Adidas, Nike etc..

This is probably one of the best shopping place to visit
If you are a shopoholic and like budget shopping, this is one place you must not miss.  From imitation bags, shoes, knick-knacks, clothes to the best freshwater and south sea pearls that you will find, its all available in this place.

Thank you for watching!

Video Title: A Day in the Life of an Expat in the Philippines | John Smulo
Video Description:
Today, let's inspect how it's like living in the Philippines as an expat compared to living abroad while I grab coffee beans for Delish Deli from The Good Cup of Coffee Company.

ğŸ“£ If you want to support me and my mission, please consider joining our channel membership. You'll get access to perks such as loyalty badges, custom emojis, priority replies, exclusive live videos, and more! Join here: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCKie0svsFyBBsKaQIA4hx-w/join ğŸ‘ˆ

A lot of you sent me questions about when things would open up here. Maybe you're planning to go on a tour around the islands, or perhaps you are moving to the Philippines from USA.

To be honest, I've already given up any hope of guessing when things would open up again. But I'm looking forward to going on a trip back to California to visit family, friends, and clients or travel around the Philippines.

I've had this John Smulo channel for about six (6) months now, and I want to get to know who is watching the videos. If you haven't left a comment or reached out to me on Facebook yet, let me know where you're watching from and what you get most out of this channel in the comments below. ğŸ‘‡

Anyway, so what's life as an expat in the Philippines like?

I also experienced challenges regarding cultural differences, and it's something you'll have to adjust to.

For one, Filipinos reacted differently when the pandemic hit. They just wanted to make it through struggles in life, unlike in the US where we have the luxury to debate whether we should wear masks.

The cost of living here also depends on how you want to live here. But there's definitely something in the Philippines for every budget.

The noises are also a major thing to get used to here. You'll hear dogs barking, roosters crowing, and karaoke sessions late at night. So it's definitely something you should consider when picking out a place to live in.

Since I came here to start a business, my experience living as an expat from other expatriates who moved here to settle and retire can be quite different.

Video Title: FROM BATANGAS TO TAGAYTAY PHILIPPINES ğŸ‡µğŸ‡­ VISITING TAAL VOLCANO to MOTHER OF ALL ASIA
Video Description:
From Batangas to Tagatay Philippines we werenâ€™t sure what to expect during our one day trip!  However, we are glad we made the drive.  From visiting TAAL VOLCANO to Mother of all Asia we made sure we got to see these standout landmarks with our very own eyes! After all weâ€™ve heard so much about them and we now know why ğŸ˜

Batangas is a province in the Calabarzon region on Luzon and is only short 2 hour drive south of Manila!  Filled with many attractions Batangas is a very popular tourist destination for Metro-Manila.  This is where we got to see Mother of All Asia in all her splendor and she did not disappoint ğŸ˜. In fact, she was more impressive in person than we had even imagined!

After our time in Batangas we made our way about an hour and half north to the province of Tagaytay.  Another popular tourist destination here we got to see the infamous Taal Volcano ğŸ˜±. Unfortunately due to a recent eruption you can no longer make your way over (the Taal Lake) to see the volcano up close and personal.  Before the eruption you used to be able to in fact climb Taal!  Hopefully one day soon we can also make our way to the top and show you all that view!!
*** FOR THE RECORD:  We know Taal Volcano's main center is in fact not the mound and crater of Binintiang Malaki: however, it is just so pretty haha â¤ï¸ ***

Needless to say we had alot of fun during our time here.  Though there is so much left to do, we walked away with a great appreciation of the area and will gladly visit again ğŸ¤— 

Thank you all for taking the time to watch our video(s), comment, and continually give us a warm welcome!  It truly means the world to us both â¤ï¸. We truly hope that you can walk away from our videos just a little bit happier than when you started or at the very least inspired even in the slightestâ€¦or heck, weâ€™ll be satisfied with a smile haha ğŸ˜Š.

Video Title: WE WERE WARNED NOT TO VISIT ZAMBOANGA CITY PHILIPPINES BUT WE DID ANYWAY ğŸ‡µğŸ‡­ (PART 1)
Video Description:
The first 1,000 people to use the link will get a 1 month free trial of Skillshare: https://skl.sh/willandjosetravels09221


Our time in the peninsula of Zamboanga has been nothing but eye opening and incredible.  Yes, Zamboanga is riddled with it's overt share of negativity but the past is just that: the past.  No place in the world is free of negative whispers and struggles that came before.  However, instead of allowing fear to keep us from making our way to the island of Mindanao we instead turned that into a flight ticket and came to see for ourselves.

Not only did we encounter some of the friendliest locals in all of the Philippines, but learned a great deal about the many cultures that call this city home, and experienced things we never thought we would experience...and we still haven't even touched the surface!!

If you are new here: WELCOME and thank you so much for taking the time out of YOUR day to support the both of us.  And if you are returning WELCOME BACK friend ğŸ¤— your faces and names always make the both of us smile and we can't wait to catch up with you all in the comments very very soon â¤ï¸

Video Title: First Impression of Cebu. Our First Grocery Shopping in the Philippines! Philippine Vlog 2022
Video Description:
Title: First Impression of Cebu. Our First Grocery Shopping in the Philippines! Philippine Vlog 2022

Welcome to a new adventure series here in Cebu. In this episode, we hit the streets of Cebu to find laundry services as well as do grocery shopping. We went without any expectations and to give an honest unfiltered reaction about Cebu. 

As soon as we hit the street, we realised the traffic here in Cebu is quite similar to Manila - very heavy traffic, but after visiting Manila we have gotten pretty used to the crossing in big traffics so it weren't too surprised. We then found a laundry place where we dropped our clothes and ticked off one thing on our to do list for the day.

For some reason, police came to us and asked us to stop recording in the middle of the CBD for unknown reasons. We were very confused as to why GoPros arent allowed to be used while phone can be used for vlogging.  

Anyway, we arrived at Ayala Mall with the hope to find supermarkets to buy groceries. We went to MarketPlace which is a reputable international supermarket which is as expected charges a more premium price, so instead we went to Metro Supermarket which is downstairs and has a wider range of products we can choose from.

Time flies and we spent an hour walking around the supermarket. In total we spent 3500 pesos for 1 week for groceries then it is time to go home.

We arrived home with a lot of thing from the supermarket and revealed what we purchased from the store and also gave a room tour about our place for the month. 

Want to see more of our vlogs in the Philippines? Subscribe to our channel now!

Video Title: Philippine Market Hunt - First Impression of Divisoria | Where to visit in Manila
Video Description:
Title: Philippine Market Hunt - First Impression of Divisoria | Where to visit in Manila

Continuing on our adventures in the Philippines, we arrived in Divisoria, a district well known for selling low-priced products and its diverse manufacturing activities. We arrived Divisoria with no expectation and was surprised by the wide range of products you can find in malls, street markets. From clothing, electronics even Chrismas decorations you can find it all here.

We arrived Divisoria via PNR which stands for Philippine National Railyway. For some reason the google map location was not accurate and we were unable to find the markets at first but luckily with the help of the locals, we managed to finally find the markets. After walking for around an hour, we  decided to buy a Ringlight for our tiktok production which costed 800 pesos. We then hit the streets and tried some street food as well which is a fried hard boiled egg skewer, together with the hot sauce it tasted amazing.

Video Description:
Kumusta YouTube Fam, 

Welcome to a new episode here in the Philippines. Ever since we arrived in the Philippines, many of our new subscribers have been recommending us to visit a beautiful area called Tagaytay, a popular holiday town south of Manila on the Philippine island Luzon. Known for its mild climate, it sits on a ridge above Taal Volcano Island, an active volcano surrounded by Taal Lake, it is one of the high recommended most beautiful places near Manila.

In this episode, we embarked on an adventure to Tagaytay by bus from Pitx in Pasay. It is our first road trip in Manila, so we did not have high expectations. Since we were the first few who got on the bus, were got to pick our own seats close to the driver, who was super friendly and talked to us the whole bus journey. 

As soon as we arrived, we checked into Anya Resort Tagaytay where we gave a brief room tour. After that we decided to venture out the resort and eat local Buko pie at a famous bakery and it was incredibly delicious.

Video Description:
Kumusta YouTube Fam, 

Welcome to a new episode here in the Philippines. Ever since we arrived in the Philippines in Novemeber 2022, we have fallen in love with filipino food because of its huge variety of dishes, tastes and affordability. 

In this episode, we embarked on a food adventure in the Philippines in a local area that I have never previously explored in the city of Taguig. Prior to coming to Taguig local area,  I never realised Taguig is this big and that BGC is only a small part of this city. Upon arriving in the area, I was already shocked by how chaotic the roads were, with jeepneys, and tricycles horning everywhere, but regardless we had 2 missions. The first is to collect an international parcel from America, and the second is to grab a delicious Filipino breakfast in the area. After collecting the parcel and walking around the streets for a while on the hunt for delicious yet safe food options, I finally found a local restaurant on the side of the road that looks seemingly safe. I ended up ordering the sizzling liempo which tasted absolutely amazing.

isang hotel na ipinapakita rin namin sa vlog na ito. Ito ang una sa dalawang hotels kung saan kami tumuloy para sa unang bahagi ng tour sa Cebu.
Makikita rin ninyo dito ang magiliw na magkasintahang Amerikano at Filipina na nagkakilala sa ChristianFilipina.com.

Video Title: Top 10 Bus Travel Guide and Tips for Philippines
Video Description:
We travel by Partas Bus Liner from Pasay Manila to La Union.  You'll see firsthand what to expect on the trip.  I also share 10 tips that should make for an easier and comfortable bus trip.  If you liked this video, hit that like button and if you want to see more of my adventures please subscribe.

Top 10 Travel Tips for riding the Bus in the Philippines

1. There are 2 major Bus terminals from Manila,  Pasay and Cubao. Depending on where you originate, you will need to decide.

2. When you get to the bus terminal, theyâ€™ll issue you a ticket with a number on it, this ticket places you in line to buy a ticket.  The wait can be 5 minutes or 5 hours. 

3.Generally, daytime is a lot busier than at night time.   We waited 3-4 hours to get on the bus during the day, but previously when we took a night bus we were able to get on the bus right away.  

4. There are 2 types of busses.  Regular bus and Deluxe bus.  If you can get on a Deluxe bus, I highly recommend the upgrade.  

5. Tell them where you are getting off.  This way they can order your luggage and stop at the correct location.

6. Snack vendors get on the bus all the time trying to sell you their goods. Be mindful of your stuff at all times.

7. Not many pee breaks, we only stopped once in our 5+ hour journey. 

8. When you do use the bathroom, youâ€™ll need to pay a few pesos.  Keep some change on you.

9. You might not like the food, so we actually packed sandwiches. 

10. The bus temperature is super cold.  Remember to bring a sweatshirt, some long pants and maybe even a blanket.

Video Title: TOP 3 things to do in CEBU CITY, Philippines
Video Description:
#cebucity #siraogardens #itsmorefuninthehilippines

It is our last day in the Philippines and there are a few sites we want to check out in Cebu City so it is off for a drive out into the country and back through the city in today's adventure.

First stop Sirao Gardens to see the famous terraces flower gardens done in the Dutch style. Looking for the famous hand sculpture? (Pro tip for finding it in the video). 

Next we are of to the Temple of Leah
templeofleah.com 
Cebu's version of the Taj Mahal.
A great neoclassical edifice built by a wealthy Filippino as a monument to his deceased wife and her treasures.

Next in the pouring rain we are off to see Magellan's Cross. This historical Monument Mark's the place where Ferdinand Magellan first set foot on the last place he would visit during his attempt to circumnavigate the world. 
Amazing!!!

Coming soon.....lunch!
To be consumed in the next video!!!

Today I went to Bonifacio Global City (BGC) in Manila, I have visited BGC twice before, but it was a few years ago. Many people have asked me to give my thoughts on BGC. I really enjoyed some great restaurants there and have previously enjoyed the nightlife! I think Bonifacio Global City would be a great place to live in Manila!

Video Title: Meeting with Apo Whang Od - The Last and Oldest Tribal Tattoo Artist - KALINGA PHILIPPINES
Video Description:
This philippines vlog is NOT your average travel vlog, this is a journey into the unknown and we want you to come with us. 
Apo Whang OD born February 17, 1917, also known as Maria Oggay, is a Filipina tattoo artist from Buscalan, Tinglayan, Kalinga, Philippines. She is often described as the "last" and oldest mambabatok (traditional Kalinga tattooist) and is part of the Butbut people of the larger Kalinga ethnic group.

She has been tattooing headhunters and women of the indigenous people of Butbut in Buscalan, Kalinga, since she was 15 years old, but the Butbut warriors who used to earn tattoos by protecting villages or removing enemies no longer exist. Despite this, Whang-od continues to practice her traditional art form on tourists visiting Buscalan.

We take the 12 hour road trip in the hope of not just meeting the legendary Whang-od but to be tattooed by her. 

There have been many foreigners who have traveled to the north of the philippines on the epic journey but this one is ours and we hope you enjoy this epic adventure and life journey.

The Mall of Asia in Manila, The Philippines is the third biggest mall in the world, and the biggest in the Philippines. In this video, we head to this mega complex to see it for ourselves, only to be blown away by its sheer size, and to get very quickly lost amongst all the world class shopping.

Video Title: My FIRST LOCAL MARKET in Manila, The Philippines! (trying ube) ğŸ‡µğŸ‡­
Video Description:
In this video, we visited some of Makati City, Manilas best food spots for our next adventure in The Philippines!

We start our day at a Philippines street market - Salcedo Saturday Market, a large open air community market that has been serving local Filipinos for over 15 years. There is so much here to discover and eat - we try Ube for the first time, as well as Filipino BBQ skewers - so good! 

We then took a long walk and ended up in the Poblacion area, checking out P. Burgos, the Main Street for Manila nightlife, where we grabbed a coffee from a cool little shop.

After that, we ended the day with a late lunch at El Chupacabra, a famous Mexican/Filipino fusion spot that served some of the best food we have had so far in Manila. We had such a great day, so come along with us to enjoy Manila, The Philippines!

Video Title: FIRST TIME IN SIARGAO + STUDIO TOUR PHILIPPINES
Video Description:
Finally we are here in Siargao Philippines, at Cloud 9 Beach. Siargao is a tropical paradise, known for its world-class surfing waves, stunning white sand, palm tree and laid-back island vibes.

We heard a lot of good things about Siargao. It is a hippy community so people are friendly and the food really surprised me, it is so delicious. The local Filipino food has better options for me and the crazy number of vegetarian options were great for Dan. Our accommodation was a 9 mins walk to cloud 9 beach. We came to cloud 9 beach to watch the surfing and beautiful sunsets every night.

Video Title: MODERN FILIPINO MALL ğŸ‡µğŸ‡­ | SM Mall of Asia in Manila, Philippines
Video Description:
Today the kids got to pick where we went and what they wanted to do! They decided to go somewhere with air conditioning: SM Mall of Asia in Manila, Philippines (also known as the Mall of Asia or MoA). Have you been here? This modern Filipino mall is huge. We thought we had entered it from the front entrance, but actually found ourselves turned around. Our first goal was to find food (that is probably NOT a surprise to you). Granite requested that we find sushi. Then, we found his favorite sushi chain called Genko Sushi. At Genko Sushi, you place your order on your phone and a bullet train delivers it to your table. Granite highly recommends this experience! 

We were looking for a trampoline or bounce park but found Laser Tag for the older kids and the Cosmic Kids play zone for Forest (Granite and Cedar did a great job chasing after him). After playing, we got a fun treat at Tiger Manju. The best way I can describe it is a fish-shaped mini waffle filled with a variety of flavored custards. Before we left the SM Mall of Asia, Cedar requested that we end the day with bubble tea. We probably spent about four hours at the mall and we barely explored it. We canâ€™t wait to come back to Manila for more adventures. 

This was our last day in Manila! It surpassed our expectations. With the festival, historical sites, and endless neighborhoods of street foods, we really needed a few more weeks here. We look forward to coming back! In our next video, we will get our bags packed and head southeast to Cebu City.

Video Title: First Time in MANILA, Philippines | First Taste of JOLLIBEEğŸ‡µğŸ‡­
Video Description:
Welcome to our Philippines series. In this video, we are flying from Kuala Lumpur to Manila with Air Asia. It's our first time visiting Manila, and we are extremely excited to explore this vibrant city.

After arriving at our Airbnb in the Makati area, we head out to the Greenbelt Mall to check out the local shops and grab some lunch. We've heard so much about Jollibee, a popular Filipino fast food chain, so we decide to give it a try for the first time.

Next, we take a walk around the local area to get to know the city and its culture. The streets are bustling with life, and we're amazed by the energy and diversity of the people.

As the day draws to a close, we head over to the CCP Bay Terminal to watch the stunning sunset over Manila Bay. It's the perfect end to our first day in this amazing city.

Join us on this exciting adventure as we explore Manila, and the Philippines, try new foods, and take in the sights and sounds of this incredible city. Don't forget to hit the like button and subscribe to our channel for more travel vlogs like this one!

Video Title: First Impressions of MANILA, Philippines | BLOWN AWAY By This MetropolisğŸ‡µğŸ‡­
Video Description:
Welcome to my YouTube video where I will be sharing my first impressions of Manila, Philippines!

Manila is a vibrant city that is often overlooked by travelers who spend very little time exploring and discovering its diversity of people, restaurants, and shopping. Makati, a popular area for first-time visitors, is a bustling commercial and financial hub that offers a glimpse of the city's modern side.

One of the most fascinating aspects of Manila is its transport system. The jeepney, a colorful and unique form of public transport, is the most popular way to get around the city. It's an experience like no other, as you hop on board and weave your way through traffic while observing the hustle and bustle of the city.

For history enthusiasts, Intramuros is a must-visit destination. This walled city within Manila feels like you've traveled back in time, with its Spanish colonial architecture and cobblestone streets. You can take a guided tour or explore the area on your own, but either way, it's an experience that will transport you to a different era.

Lastly, I visited the beautiful Rizal Park, named after the national hero, Dr. Jose Rizal. The park is a massive urban green space that offers a break from the hustle and bustle of the city. It's a popular spot for locals and tourists alike, with its gardens, monuments, and fountains that make for a picturesque backdrop for photos.

Overall, my first impressions of Manila were that it's a city that is full of life, culture, and history. There is so much to discover, and I highly recommend spending more than just a few days in this bustling city to truly appreciate all that it has to offer.

Video Title: First Time in Manila, Philippines! Eating Jollibee, taking the metro, and visiting tourist places
Video Description:
We are finally exploring Manila! When we first arrived in the Philippines we were immediately invited to a family party in Pampanga, so it has taken us a little longer than we expected to explore the Philippines capital city; Manila. There are so many tourist places to explore in Manila, so we chose the best tourist spots according to our taste and are excited to share our first day exploring Manila with you.

First up, we visited Bonifacio Global City (BGC) which is a luxury piece of Manila that attracts many foreigners because it is very safe and has all the comforts that Western foreigners are used to. The shopping and coffee are amazing, but what really makes this place worth visiting are the free-roaming cats and the dogs in strollers!

Then, to really get a feel for the city, we took the Manila Metro! The metro was CROWDED, but, it ran well and was really affordable. We love taking public transportation when we get to a new city, and Manila is a great place to learn how to use the metro system because Manila traffic is terrible (seriously, we can't emphasize this enough!). If you are a traveler visiting Manila, we highly recommend learning how to take the metro system to save yourself money and a few headaches :)

After our packed metro experience, we rewarded ourselves with Jollibee! For me (Nicole) it was my first time trying Jollibee, and boy did visiting Jollibee make a lot of things about Mico make sense! You'll have to watch the video for all of the details, but when we left Jollibee's I felt like I had put a few pieces of the puzzle of Mico together at last. Maybe it really is true that Jollibee is part of the fabric of being Filipino, even for those Filipino who have been living outside of the Philippines for many years :)

With the energy to explore (actually fried chicken made us feel tired haha) we visited Rizal Park and learned a bit about the Filipino patriot, Jose Rizal. After touring Rizal Park we made our way to Intramuros - a very popular tourist spot in Manila. Intramuros is a beautiful area that gave us a chance to learn more about the Spanish conquest in the Philippines. We saw the gorgeous Manila Cathedral and ended our day with a visit to Fort Santiago. And if you watch to the end of the video, you'll see a very interesting shot of a man rowing a boat with what we think was cardboard (I thought it was impressive :p)

Video Title: $20 First Class Bus (to Philippines Coldest City) ğŸ‡µğŸ‡­
Video Description:
I was fed up of Manila's scorching heat so I boarded a bus out of town. My destination being the coldest city in the Philippines.

Baguio is known as the 'Summer Capital' of the Philippines and is very popular with domestic tourists looking for a break from the roasting hot weather in their own province.

There are direct buses running between Manila and Baguio very frequently, but there are different classes with different levels of comfort. Given that it was to be a 6 hour journey (depending on the traffic) I made sure to book the highest category of bus, 'First Class'.

There are many different bus companies in Luzon but I don't think there's much difference between them in terms of service and comfort. I chose to go with Victory Liner.

At the Victory Liner bus station in Pasay there's a dedicated waiting room for first class passenger. Nothing fancy, just some tea, coffee and a TV, but the main thing is the air conditioning. I was able to sit in comfort until the bus was ready to depart.

The first class bus has a 1-2 seating arrangement, so it's possible to book a seat alone without someone next to you. That's perfect for someone like me travelling solo. You don't want to be touching arms with a stranger for 6 hours like on some budget airline.

It didn't even take 6 hours though. The bus took ages to get out of Manila, due to the ridiculous traffic, but after that the roads were clear and we arrived in Baguio much sooner than I expected.

I thought the ticket price of 1,049 PHP ($18.63) was worth it for all the space I had, but other than that there's nothing fancy about the bus. No individual entertainment units, charging ports, anything like that.

The Victory Liner terminal in Baguio is located directly opposite a Jollibee restaurant so the first thing I did in Baguio was enjoy a delicious Double Yumburger.

I then checked in to the Orchard Hotel. It was the best hotel I could find in the central area of Baguio. There were some better hotels but they were in more remote areas.

My room at Orchard Hotel was hardly perfect, but the view from the balcony was awesome.

Getting close to sunset, I decided to visit the huge hangout area in the centre of Baguio called Burnham Park. There were loads of vendors selling ice cream and other treats, and a huge lake where people were enjoying boat rides.

So after enjoying a "special" strawberry ice cream, that I've no idea what was so special about it, I jumped on a pontoon and did a lap of the lake.

As the sun set, I got myself another sweet treat, a special "Ice Scramble" which is something like a Halo-halo and headed back to my hotel to enjoy a room service massage. Life is good.

Video Title: $0.25 Burger in Baguio, Philippines ğŸ‡µğŸ‡­
Video Description:
I explored the 'Summer Capital' of the Philippines. Baguio is a mountain city in Luzon that's very popular with domestic tourists looking for some fresher weather.

A cooler climate is exactly what I needed after suffering in the sweltering heat of Manila. After travelling to Baguio I can finally roam around outdoors for hours and feel good.

I started my day at the SM City. It's a huge modern mall built on top of a hill, with open walls to let the cool air flow through. It's the only major mall in the Philippines without air conditioning. AC simply isn't needed in Baguio.

At SM City Baguio, I enjoyed a combination of two of my favourite drinks, Milo and Boba Milk Tea from a stall called Tiger Sugar. I took my delicious drink to the sky terrace on the roof of the mall, that is a popular place to hang out and enjoy the weather and view of Baguio city.

I could see a Ferris wheel near the mall so went to check it out. It was in the Sky Ranch amusement park which has some other rides, but the only one that interested me was the pirate ship. It was fun but I wish there were some more thrill rides there.

From there I walked down Session Road, the main street in Baguio, to visit the public market. My mission was to buy some fresh strawberries, and that was an easy one to complete. Strawberries are very popular in Baguio as the area has the perfect climate to grow them.

At Baguio Public Market I also enjoyed some strawberry ice cream and some delicious Filipino sweets made from cassava and ube.

My final mission of the day was to buy a Baguio t-shirt and that was neither difficult of expensive.

With my missions complete I rewarded myself with a burger. I saw many people queuing up at a bakery where dozens of burgers were being fried up. No wonder they are popular as it must be the cheapest burger in the world, at only 15 pesos, or about $0.25. What a bargain!

The next day I continued the vlog by getting outside of Baguio city centre and visiting a cultural village at Mount Kalugong. The weather forecast was for heavy rain but I packed a poncho and visited anyway. The forecast is for rain every day, so you just need to take your chances.

After a short hike around the mountain and a bit of rock climbing, I was surprised to see there was a coffee shop up there. I don't like coffee but they had matcha green tea, which I love. So I got to enjoy a nice cold match Frappuccino with an incredible view of the La Trinidad area.

I visited Mr Kalugong by taxi but returned with the local transport, a jeepney. I've seen jeepneys everywhere since I arrived in the Philippines but had never actually ridden in one, so this was my first time.

I ended my Baguio adventure back where I began it, at the SM City Mall, where I enjoyed some special Japanese ramen and another bubble tea. Yum yum!

Video Title: Random Filipina Wants to Massage Me in Bohol ğŸ‡µğŸ‡­
Video Description:
I escaped the big city of Manila in the search for more tropical surroundings.

I'm not much of a beach person, so I researched to find an island that would have more to offer than just sunbathing and snorkeling. Bohol seemed like a good option, as it's is famous for its 'Chocolate Hills' - an amazing geological formation in the centre of the island. It would be a good place to rent a motorbike and explore.

On my first day, however I planned to enjoy the fancy beach resort that I'd booked at $250 USD per night.

I stayed at Henann Resort, which is beside Alona Beach in Panglao. Panglao is actually a separate, smaller island to Bohol, connected by a bridge but it's still part of the Bohol regency.

I was happy with my room, or "suite" they called it, at the Hennan hotel, other than the desk / chair set up that didn't have enough room for my legs. A common annoyance at hotels around the world. Who designs these things???

The hotel has many large pools and is right next to the beach, so plenty of swimming opportunities. That's what I was going to do, until I saw that kayaking was available. They were a special type of kayak called Crystal Kayaks that are totally see-through.  Perfect for kayaking in tropical waters.

I didn't see any tropical fish, kayaking so close to the beach, but I did see some cool looking crabs and some jellyfish.

After I worked up an appetite paddling around in the sea, I headed to the executive lounge to enjoy some snacks. As I'd paid for a suite, it included access to the Hennan lounge where food and drink is free.

I ended my first day in Bohol with a relaxing sunset beach massage. The lady who massaged me was strong and skilled, but then a random Filipina lady came by and asked if she could massage me instead. So random but so funny.

Video Title: Off The Beaten Path GOES WRONG in Bohol, Philippines ğŸ‡µğŸ‡­
Video Description:
I rented a motorbike so I could explore the Bohol island easily and in peace, without being stuck with a guide and driver.

There were many bike rental shops near my hotel, so I chose the one that had the best reviews on Google Maps. It cost 400 pesos ($7.20 USD) per day, while other shops were renting for 300 pesos per day, but their bikes were fairly new and in perfect condition, so it was worth paying the premium price.

For my first day of exploring I stayed in Panglao, which is the small island that's attached to the big Bohol island by a bridge.

Feeling hungry, I drove to Fortridge Food Park, which was highly rated on Google Maps, but when I got there it was dead. I think I was the only customer there and most restaurants were closed. So it seems like it's an evening place. Don't waste your time, like me, going there in the afternoon.

I ordered a fresh pineapple shake at Fortridge and then a huge thunderstorm started. So I took shelter there until it was dry, and continued my adventure.

I drove across Panglao to the Hinagdanan Cave, which is a popular tourist site in Bohol. It was way too busy though, with a queue of people waiting to get inside.

It was mostly local Filipino tourists who were visiting the cave. Bohol is a popular domestic tourist location, especially at the weekends. Filipinos living in Cebu can easily take a ferry across to Bohol for the weekend.

It was Sunday, and so I decided I'd leave and come back to the cave on a weekday.

It seemed like it was going to be a completely wasted day. With only a couple of hours of daylight left I tried to find something else interesting to visit in Panglao. I found there was seashell museum not too far away, and I could make it there just before they closed for the day.

The Nova Shell Museum in the Poblacion area of Panglao is one of the world's biggest sea shell collections in the world. I was lucky enough to go there when there were less visitors, so I got a  private tour of the collection from one of the knowledgeable guides there.

The next day started off rainy and I waited for a dry spell, so I could drive to Chocolate Hills on the main Bohol island.

I have access to the executive lounge at the Henann Alona Beach hotel where I'm staying, I so relaxed in there with some free snacks and drinks for a while.

Eventually the rain stopped and I started the 2 hour road trip to Bohol's Chocolate Hills. But on the way I stopped to visit the tarsiers.

Tarsiers are little monkeys and there's a big conservation area of them on the way to Chocolate Hills. They are nocturnal so they aren't moving around during the daytime but you can see them relaxing in the trees.

The other tourists I met at the the Bohol Tarsier Conservation Area were all heading to the Chocolate Hills viewpoint but I had a better idea. Rather than visit the tourist viewpoint, I found a place on Google Maps that said "Chocolate Hill free view point."

I reached the exact point on the map but there was nothing there, so I had to do a bit of exploring. I thought I found a path but that just led to me falling in a ditch and then discovering a locked gate.

After getting some help from the locals I eventually found my way up one of the chocolate hills, that I got to enjoy all by myself with no tourists to annoy me. Despite the mishap, it felt like a great success!

I looked for somewhere to enjoy some tasty Filipino food on my journey back to Panglao, and found a restaurant called "Don Lechon." Lechon is rotisserie pig - a food that I've been meaning to try since I got to the Philippines but haven't found the authentic one yet.

I thought I'd get the authentic pork lechon at Don Lechon, but it was only chicken. Apparently chicken can also be lechon.

On my last day in Bohol, before returning my scooter, I finally visited the Hinagdanan Cave and I have to say it was underwhelming. It's just a cave with a pool of water. It's cool to look at for a few seconds but that's it. Most people were there to swim, but I passed on that, as it didn't look clean.

I ended my Bohol adventure with a fruit smoothie, made by friendly local woman.

I recommend renting a motorbike if you visit Bohol. It was the best way to explore this amazing island.

Video Title: De ce nu ne-a placut Manila - Filipine
Video Description:
De ce nu ne-a placut Manila - Filipine - vlog de calatorie ep 48

A venit momentul sa ne luam ramas bun de la Filipine si sa imbratisam o noua tara, sa o cunoastem si sa o exploram. Pentru a face legatura intre insulele din Filipine si noua destinatie, mai intai trebuie sa petrecem o noapte si o jumatate de zi in Manila. Initial voiam sa alocam mai mult timp capitalei Filipinelor, insa ne-am documentat temeinic si am decis ca less is more ğŸ™‚ 
Am aterizat seara din Bohol in Manila si inca de la aeroport am facut cunostinta cu stilul lor de pacalit turistii. Doi taximetristi ne-au cerut pe cursa pana in Makati, cartierul in care avem hotelul, de peste 10 ori pretul cursei. In aeroport exista o zona cu taxiuri autorizate si o domna care iti aproximeaza costul cursei, astfel incat soferul sa nu te pacaleasca. Credeti ca soferii tin cont de aceasta aproximare? Nu! ğŸ™‚ gasesc motive diverse pentru care vor creste costul cursei.
Am ajuns la hotel, camera este mica si stinghera, costul ei destul de mare, dar hotelul este pozitionat fix in centru Makati-ului, in zona de restaurante si cafenele. Am lasat bagajele si am iesit sa cautam un restaurant decent ğŸ™‚ cam greu, zicem noi. Am cutreierat stradutele pline de localnici, turisti si bisnitari. Un sentiment de frica mi-a paralizat mana pe geanta si ne-a marit pasul. Nu ne simteam in largul nostru, oamenii ne pareau ciudati si aveam impresia ca la orice colt de strada mai intunecat ne gasim nasul. Este primul oras care nu ne atrage si pe care nu ne dorim sa il descoperim. Ne da un sentiment de neliniste. Am gasit un restaurant ok-ish, mancam pe fuga si mergem repejor la culcare, maine vrem sa vedem daca ne schimbam parerea despre Manila.
De dimineata aveam mari dubii ca vrem sa exploram orasul, dar am decis sa vedem un parc, Alaya, care este o oaza de verdeata si liniste. Ne-am plimbat picioarele pana la un mall din apropiere, incadrat de un alt parc si ziua a trecut extrem de repede in aceste locuri unde ne-am simtit in  siguranta, datorita famiilor cu copii si atmosferei prietenoase. 
Manila este un oras al contrastelor, multa saracie dar si opulenta, al localnicilor care vor sa castige cat mai mult de pe urma turismului, al cluburilor de noapte din Makati, al femeilor care renunta la feminitate pentru un venit, al copiilor care dorm pe scari, al cladirilor pana la cer, al tranzitului din insulele filipineze spre alta tara.
Noi nu ne vom mai intoarce in Manila decat pentru a accesa insulele din Filipine,  care sunt un rai inca rustic al Asiei de Sud Est.

Video Title: What Commuting in Philippines' Capital (Manila) is Like
Video Description:
When I talked to friends and the Life Where I'm From community about going to the capital city of the Philippines, Manila, many warned me about the traffic. One community member even offered to show me her commute, so of course, I jumped at the opportunity.

At first I thought, oh yeah, everyone complains about their area's drivers, and the congestion is bad, and you know, here it's the worst. But after reading some reports, traffic in the Philippines, and especially Manila, really is some of the worst in the world.

I've filmed a lot about the Philippines, so I might be making 2-3 more videos, and perhaps one that talks specifically about Manila's Traffic problem.

What's the commute like where you're from?

Video Title: SOLO TRAVEL TO THE PHILIPPINES | First Impressions of Manila
Video Description:
Manila is a city of 15 million people and considered by some as the most dangerous large city in South East Asia. As a solo female traveler I knew it would be important to take the necessary precautions when traveling here, but I was overall quite surprised with what I experienced. Join me as I tour some of the cities most popular districts like Makati, BCG and Intramuros and give you my first impressions. And of course I had to try Jollibee because that is definitely a Filipino culture staple! Hope you guys enjoy the video and come check out Manila for yourself! xx

Video Title: Cebu Motorcycle Tour, Philippines, Scary! but fun, Solo!
Video Description:
Enjoy some outstanding motorcycle adventure roads in this 4K Cebu Philippines motorcycle, motorbike tour to the Cebu highlands. This was my first ride on a motorbike in Cebu, or ever in the Philippines for that matter, and my first impressions of riding a motorcycle there.   
Cebu Philippines, is a scary city in a lot of ways, and my first Impressions were that it was going to be difficult riding a Motorcycle there for the first time in the very busy and chaotic streets!

After being a bit nervous leaving my hotel car park I almost immediately felt at home again on a motorcycle seat riding through the crazy traffic, and it turned out to be one of the best adventure rides I have done so far on road. So I hope you enjoy the ride as much I did doing it. 
See you out there, and thanks for watching.

Video Title: Batad, Philippines | The Lost Village of Rice Terraces
Video Description:
Batad, Philippines. It's a small village situated among huge rice terraces and beautiful views. The village is near Banaue, which is a ten hour bus ride from Manila. If you want to see rice terraces in The Philippines, or even all of Southeast Asia, this is the place to go. I spent two days hiking the massive terraces and taking in the beauty of it all. Watch to witness a breathtaking landscape.

Video Title: Visiting a $1 Zoo in The Philippines | Albay Park & Wildlife and LigÃ±on Hill ğŸ‡µğŸ‡­
Video Description:
Hello Guys! Welcome, and in this Philippines travel vlog, I will explore Albay Park & Wildlife and hike to the top of LigÃ±on Hill for an epic view of Legazpi City.

â–¶ï¸ Please Subscribe: https://www.youtube.com/@RobbieTravels

Today I visited Albay Park and Wildlife, a zoo park in Legazpi City, Philippines. The park is home to various animals, including tigers, lions, snakes, peacocks, and many more. The animals are  cared for by the City Veterinary Services. The park is safe, as most animals are housed in large cages where they can freely move around, some animal species aren't that lucky asI feltvery sad for the lion and the tiger.

In addition to seeing the animals, I also enjoyed spending time in the park's picnic grove. There are plenty of tables and benches where you can relax and enjoy a meal. There is also a playground for children and a fishing pond.

If you're looking for a fun and affordable way to spend a day in Legazpi City, I highly recommend visiting Albay Park and Wildlife.

After visiting Albay Park and Wildlife, I visited LigÃ±on Hill, another popular tourist destination in Legazpi City. LigÃ±on Hill is a 156-meter-high hill that offers stunning views of the city, Mayon Volcano, and Albay Bay.

There are a few different ways to get to the top of LigÃ±on Hill. You can walk, hike, or take a taxi. The hike is about 30 minutes long and is a quite steep climb. There seems to be a jeepney ride as well, but it can be quite crowded.

But I have decided to take a hike as it is a great way to exercise. Once I reached the top of the hill, I was amazed at the stunning views of the city, Mayon Volcano, and Albay Bay. There is a viewing platform to enjoy the views. Don't forget to bring your own refreshments because everything was closed at the top of LigÃ±on Hill.

Also, If you're feeling adventurous, try the 320-meter zip line from the top of the hill to the bottom. The zip line is a great way to get a bird's-eye view of the city and the surrounding area. Unfortunately the zip line was closed when we arrived there. I hope it was just a temporary closure.

I highly recommend visiting LigÃ±on Hill if you're looking for a fun and challenging activity. The views from the top of the hill are simply amazing.
So, watch the video till the end and donâ€™t forget to share your thoughts in the comments.

Video Title: Philippines travel - From Ho Chi Minh city to Puerto Princesa, Palawan
Video Description:
Philippines travel from Ho Chi Minh city to Puerto Princesa, Palawan

Sharing the first day of our 2 week Philippines trip, IMPORTANT NOTICES about flights and airport issues in Manila. 

Puerto Princesa, officially the City of Puerto Princesa, and often referred to as Puerto Princesa City, is a 1st class Highly Urbanized City in the Philippines. According to the 2015 census, it has a population of 255,116 people.

It is a city located in the western province of Palawan, and westernmost city in the Philippines. Though the seat of government and capital for the province, the city itself is one of 38 independent cities within the Philippines not controlled by the province in which it is geographically located and is therefore an independent area located within Palawan.

Today, Puerto Princesa is a popular tourist city with many beach resorts and seafood restaurants. It has been acclaimed several times as the cleanest and greenest city in the Philippines.
